371
00:21:56.974 --> 00:22:00.554
I'm Patrick Kerwin from the Califano Lab at Columbia University.

372
00:22:01.414 --> 00:22:01.694
Sorry.

373
00:22:04.174 --> 00:22:07.934
Today, I'll present our work using high-throughput drug screening and single-cell

374
00:22:07.994 --> 00:22:11.834
network analysis to identify rational combination therapies in IDH

375
00:22:11.894 --> 00:22:12.574
mutant glioma.

376
00:22:13.874 --> 00:22:14.994
Here are my disclosures.

377
00:22:16.674 --> 00:22:20.394
So adult diffuse gliomas split into IDH wild type and IDH

378
00:22:20.494 --> 00:22:24.394
mutant. What I'll focus on today is IDH mutant glioma,

379
00:22:24.934 --> 00:22:28.594
which separates into two diseases, oligodendroglioma and astrocytoma.

380
00:22:29.274 --> 00:22:33.254
As the survival curves show, oligodendroglioma patients tend to do the best.

381
00:22:33.634 --> 00:22:37.594
Astrocytomas are intermediate, and IDH wild type glioblastoma has

382
00:22:37.614 --> 00:22:41.414
the worst outcomes. But critically, even in the better prognosis

383
00:22:41.474 --> 00:22:42.454
IDH mutant tumors,

384
00:22:43.394 --> 00:22:46.314
these tumors inevitably progress and are uniformly fatal.

385
00:22:49.414 --> 00:22:51.494
Two key factors drive treatment failure.

386
00:22:51.534 --> 00:22:53.494
The first is single cell heterogeneity.

387
00:22:53.734 --> 00:22:57.134
So the IDH mutation driving this disease produces the

388
00:22:57.174 --> 00:22:59.954
onco-metabolite 2-hydroxyglutarate, or 2HG.

389
00:23:01.034 --> 00:23:04.794
2HG drives global hypermethylation, both at the DNA and histone

390
00:23:04.834 --> 00:23:08.714
levels that lock cells into multiple differentiation impaired

391
00:23:08.774 --> 00:23:09.114
states.

392
00:23:10.174 --> 00:23:13.634
The current standard of care, which includes resection, chemoradiation, and more

393
00:23:13.694 --> 00:23:17.474
recently, IDH inhibition, tends to achieve disease stabilization for some

394
00:23:17.534 --> 00:23:21.384
time, but there's eventually progression because this heterogeneity is not

395
00:23:21.394 --> 00:23:25.284
addressed. So in other words, current therapy is successful in

396
00:23:25.314 --> 00:23:28.714
buying time while preserving quality of life, but it's not curative.

397
00:23:31.194 --> 00:23:34.294
So with the disease context in mind, our objective is to identify and

398
00:23:34.314 --> 00:23:38.294
therapeutically target cell state-specific dependencies in IDH mutant glioma

399
00:23:38.304 --> 00:23:41.664
and design rational combinations that go beyond disease

400
00:23:41.734 --> 00:23:45.054
stabilization. And our approach has three parts.

401
00:23:45.314 --> 00:23:48.874
First, we define state dependencies by building an IDH mutant regulatory

402
00:23:48.934 --> 00:23:52.614
network and inferring the master regulators that control each malignant state.

403
00:23:53.374 --> 00:23:57.134
Second, we turn these MR programs into drug predictions using high-throughput

404
00:23:57.194 --> 00:24:00.954
perturbational data in MR-matched cell lines, identifying the

405
00:24:00.994 --> 00:24:04.394
compounds that selectively invert each state's regulatory program.

406
00:24:05.074 --> 00:24:08.814
And finally, we validate single agents and combinations in patient-derived

407
00:24:08.834 --> 00:24:12.554
acute slice explants with single-cell readouts, testing whether the

408
00:24:12.594 --> 00:24:16.454
targeted states in fact contract or shift as predicted.

409
00:24:18.834 --> 00:24:22.374
We generated over 250,000 single-nucleus RNA-seq

410
00:24:22.434 --> 00:24:26.414
profiles from 20 primary treatment-naive resections, 10

411
00:24:26.454 --> 00:24:30.214
oligodendrogliomas, and 10 astrocytomas sourced from the Columbia

412
00:24:30.274 --> 00:24:33.354
Biobank. And importantly, enrichment analysis

413
00:24:34.154 --> 00:24:37.634
using established gene sets confirmed the presence of previously described

414
00:24:38.114 --> 00:24:41.654
MPC-like, OC-like, and AC-like malignant cell states

415
00:24:42.014 --> 00:24:45.154
across both oligodendroglioma and astrocytoma

416
00:24:45.174 --> 00:24:49.006
tumors.So what are master regulators?

417
00:24:49.146 --> 00:24:52.766
So master regulators are transcriptional bottlenecks that funnel diverse

418
00:24:52.866 --> 00:24:56.306
upstream mutations into stable tumor cell states.

419
00:24:57.006 --> 00:24:59.046
To identify them, we use a two-step pipeline.

420
00:24:59.726 --> 00:25:03.346
First, Arachne reverse engineers a gene regulatory network from

421
00:25:03.385 --> 00:25:06.726
expression data, linking each regulator to the genes it controls.

422
00:25:07.296 --> 00:25:11.006
Then Viper infers a regulator's protein activity not from its own

423
00:25:11.066 --> 00:25:14.466
mRNA, but from the coordinated behavior of its targets.

424
00:25:14.646 --> 00:25:18.506
So if a regulator is active, its positively regulated target should be up,

425
00:25:18.876 --> 00:25:22.046
and its negatively regulated target should be down.

426
00:25:22.255 --> 00:25:25.706
The output is a small set of master regulators that establish and maintain each

427
00:25:25.746 --> 00:25:29.666
malignant state. So instead of calling a cell NPC-like because

428
00:25:29.746 --> 00:25:33.606
marker X is high, we ask which MR program is enforcing the

429
00:25:33.686 --> 00:25:37.606
NPC-like state. So a mechanistic state definition rather than a

430
00:25:37.615 --> 00:25:40.266
descriptive one. And because MR sit at the

431
00:25:40.286 --> 00:25:44.166
convergence point

432
00:25:44.446 --> 00:25:47.946
of upstream alterations, they give us an actionable therapeutic handle.

433
00:25:47.986 --> 00:25:50.886
You target the MR program, and you can collapse the cell state.

434
00:25:53.026 --> 00:25:56.746
So now that we've defined cell states in the protein activity space, the next

435
00:25:56.786 --> 00:26:00.766
question is whether their master regulator programs are conserved across patients

436
00:26:00.886 --> 00:26:03.506
and histologies. That's what this heat map is showing.

437
00:26:03.606 --> 00:26:07.506
The columns are single cells grouped by state, AC, NPC,

438
00:26:07.816 --> 00:26:11.806
and OC-like, and the color is Viper activity, with red being high and blue being

439
00:26:11.846 --> 00:26:11.986
low.

440
00:26:12.846 --> 00:26:14.436
And the pattern we see is pretty clear.

441
00:26:14.706 --> 00:26:18.366
AC and OC-like have coherent but

442
00:26:18.426 --> 00:26:22.346
largely orthogonal MR modules, and NPC-like sits

443
00:26:22.826 --> 00:26:25.526
between them, sharing part of the OC-like program.

444
00:26:25.546 --> 00:26:29.506
But the key takeaway is that these state-defining MR programs are conserved

445
00:26:29.546 --> 00:26:32.166
across both oligodendroglioma and astrocytoma.

446
00:26:32.586 --> 00:26:32.866
That's the

447
00:26:34.146 --> 00:26:34.376
blue and

448
00:26:35.946 --> 00:26:36.906
purple you see at the top there.

449
00:26:38.146 --> 00:26:41.986
So these are two genetically distinct diseases that nonetheless converge on the

450
00:26:42.046 --> 00:26:45.826
same regulatory architecture at the cell state level.

451
00:26:46.046 --> 00:26:49.586
This means our therapeutic strategy can generalize across these glioma

452
00:26:49.606 --> 00:26:52.026
subtypes and critically serve across patients.

453
00:26:54.986 --> 00:26:58.345
Zooming in, each tumor state is defined by its own master regulator program.

454
00:26:58.486 --> 00:27:02.306
In the AC-like state, this represents an astrocytic malignant

455
00:27:02.316 --> 00:27:06.296
program defined by Hes4-driven Notch signaling, Sox9-mediated

456
00:27:06.326 --> 00:27:09.706
astrocytic lineage identity, and Id4-sustained plasticity.

457
00:27:10.426 --> 00:27:14.306
In the NPC-like state, we're seeing a progenitor-like malignant state defined by

458
00:27:14.366 --> 00:27:16.706
EGFR-driven growth signaling,

459
00:27:17.166 --> 00:27:20.155
Neuroligin-1-associated neurodevelopmental identity, and

460
00:27:20.386 --> 00:27:22.796
Chd9-linked chromatin plasticity.

461
00:27:23.286 --> 00:27:26.596
This is consistent with a population that's primed for growth, invasion, and

462
00:27:26.766 --> 00:27:30.606
adaptive reprogramming. The OC-like state represents an

463
00:27:30.626 --> 00:27:34.046
oligodendroglial malignant program in which

464
00:27:34.086 --> 00:27:38.076
Gpr17 and Sox10 enforce a canonical progenitor identity,

465
00:27:38.626 --> 00:27:42.086
while Bpm2 reinforces the oligodendroglial

466
00:27:42.366 --> 00:27:45.926
differentiation block. So critically, each of these programs

467
00:27:45.986 --> 00:27:48.516
implies a distinct therapeutic vulnerability.

468
00:27:51.006 --> 00:27:54.566
So with the state-specific MR programs defined, the next question was: Which drugs

469
00:27:54.606 --> 00:27:56.666
are most likely to collapse each cell state?

470
00:27:57.086 --> 00:28:00.786
To answer this, we used PlateSeq, a high-throughput drug perturbation platform.

471
00:28:01.486 --> 00:28:05.426
We treated MR-matched, patient-derived cell lines with a library of

472
00:28:05.586 --> 00:28:09.516
372 FDA-approved and investigational oncology compounds,

473
00:28:10.076 --> 00:28:13.486
then profiled the transcriptomic response to each drug versus vehicle control.

474
00:28:14.046 --> 00:28:17.746
Treatments were at the IC20 for 24 hours, the goal being to capture early

475
00:28:17.886 --> 00:28:20.346
regulatory changes, not end-stage toxicity.

476
00:28:21.286 --> 00:28:24.406
And the result is a perturbational profile for each drug that we can compare

477
00:28:24.446 --> 00:28:27.266
against the MR programs defining each tumor state.

478
00:28:30.986 --> 00:28:34.866
We then use OncoTreat to rank compounds by how strongly they invert

479
00:28:34.986 --> 00:28:38.106
the master regulator module sustaining each state.

480
00:28:38.346 --> 00:28:42.326
In other words, how effectively each drug is predicted to collapse that state's

481
00:28:42.366 --> 00:28:43.226
regulatory program.

482
00:28:44.146 --> 00:28:47.886
To do this, we compared Viper protein activity signatures in drug-treated versus

483
00:28:47.946 --> 00:28:50.826
vehicle control cells and asked how well each perturbation

484
00:28:50.886 --> 00:28:54.796
flips the top activated and repressed MRs defined in

485
00:28:54.826 --> 00:28:57.746
each state. The output is a drug-by-state

486
00:28:57.826 --> 00:29:01.586
matrix scored by the significance of MR conversion.

487
00:29:02.066 --> 00:29:05.406
Here we're reporting as minus log base 10 of FDR,

488
00:29:06.006 --> 00:29:09.766
where higher scores indicate stronger predicted reversal of the malignant

489
00:29:09.806 --> 00:29:13.346
program. So conceptually, this lets us ask two complementary

490
00:29:13.386 --> 00:29:17.186
questions. Which drugs normalize a malignant MR program,

491
00:29:17.506 --> 00:29:19.386
and which may drive state transitions?

492
00:29:19.646 --> 00:29:23.466
For example, pushing a more stem-like NPC population towards a more

493
00:29:23.506 --> 00:29:25.046
differentiated OC-like state.

494
00:29:25.886 --> 00:29:29.616
And that gives us a rational basis for prioritizing state-selective drugs and

495
00:29:29.706 --> 00:29:30.306
combinations.

496
00:29:33.406 --> 00:29:37.326
So although OncoTreat nominates mechanistically diverse drugs, the hits for

497
00:29:37.366 --> 00:29:40.626
each state converge on a small number of core vulnerabilities.

498
00:29:41.296 --> 00:29:44.966
So in the AC-like state, cisplatin and enibritib both target DNA

499
00:29:44.986 --> 00:29:48.626
damage and repair as a key weakness, exploiting the HR repair

500
00:29:48.646 --> 00:29:51.066
vulnerability of IDH-mutant cells.

501
00:29:51.206 --> 00:29:55.166
In the NPC-like state, DS 651b and dabrafenib

502
00:29:55.226 --> 00:29:58.656
both suppress MAP case signaling, the dominant growth dependency in this

503
00:29:59.026 --> 00:30:01.266
stem-like proliferative compartment.

504
00:30:01.386 --> 00:30:05.286
And in the OC state, micofenolate and thioguanine both

505
00:30:05.346 --> 00:30:08.726
hit purine synthesis, pointing to a metabolic

506
00:30:08.846 --> 00:30:11.586
vulnerability specific to this program.

507
00:30:11.626 --> 00:30:15.606
The key point is that across the three malignant states, OncoTreat identified three

508
00:30:15.646 --> 00:30:19.426
distinct vulnerability programs, each actionable

509
00:30:19.466 --> 00:30:20.626
with existing compounds.

510
00:30:23.146 --> 00:30:25.046
So lastly, we move into ex vivo validation.

511
00:30:25.366 --> 00:30:28.126
Here we're using patient-derived acute slice explants.

512
00:30:28.346 --> 00:30:32.246
That's freshly resected tumor tissue that's sectioned and treated within

513
00:30:32.256 --> 00:30:35.846
hours of surgery. So unlike cell lines, these preserve the native

514
00:30:35.866 --> 00:30:39.666
human tissue architecture, cell-cell interactions, spatial niches,

515
00:30:39.746 --> 00:30:43.366
and microenvironmental context that gets erased in standard

516
00:30:43.426 --> 00:30:43.806
models.

517
00:30:44.726 --> 00:30:48.006
So the slices are treated with our candidate single agents as well as combinations,

518
00:30:48.126 --> 00:30:50.986
and we profile cell state changes by single-nucleus

519
00:30:51.086 --> 00:30:54.914
RNA-seq.This lets us ask not just does the tumor respond, but which

520
00:30:54.994 --> 00:30:58.934
compartments respond and how. And the results of the

521
00:30:58.994 --> 00:31:02.834
first compound set are ongoing, and we expect initial readout in the coming months.

522
00:31:05.334 --> 00:31:08.744
So to summarize, this is a mechanism-based approach to prioritizing

523
00:31:08.874 --> 00:31:11.574
combination strategies for IDH mutant glioma.

524
00:31:11.674 --> 00:31:14.954
We start from the master regulators that maintain each malignant cell state, then

525
00:31:15.014 --> 00:31:16.414
identify drugs that disable them.

526
00:31:16.994 --> 00:31:20.974
We select compounds by their ability to invert a state's regulatory program, not

527
00:31:20.994 --> 00:31:24.723
by whether they simply kill cells. And three findings frame our results.

528
00:31:25.194 --> 00:31:29.174
First, single nucleus network analysis revealed conserved state-specific

529
00:31:29.214 --> 00:31:32.374
master regulator programs across IDH mutant glioma subtypes.

530
00:31:33.094 --> 00:31:36.654
Second, OncoTree prioritized state-specific drug

531
00:31:36.714 --> 00:31:40.134
candidates with distinct mechanisms for the AC,

532
00:31:40.594 --> 00:31:44.354
NPC, and OC-like populations. And third, because these states and their

533
00:31:44.394 --> 00:31:47.334
vulnerabilities are conserved across patients and histologies,

534
00:31:48.074 --> 00:31:51.914
validated combinations should generalize broadly rather than being tied to a

535
00:31:51.954 --> 00:31:52.554
single tumor.

536
00:31:53.614 --> 00:31:57.234
So looking ahead, we're using the explant validation to test which predicted drugs

537
00:31:57.433 --> 00:32:01.354
truly deplete or reprogram each target state, and the most promising agents

538
00:32:01.374 --> 00:32:04.924
and combinations will then be validated in vivo in a recently

539
00:32:04.934 --> 00:32:08.274
published genetically engineered mouse model developed by our collaborators.

540
00:32:09.154 --> 00:32:13.034
Together, this gives us a rational path to combination therapy for a

541
00:32:13.054 --> 00:32:16.154
disease where current approaches remain largely non-curative.

542
00:32:18.794 --> 00:32:22.374
I want to thank the Califano lab, especially Andrea Califano, Luca Zinella, and

543
00:32:22.414 --> 00:32:26.094
Mikko Turunen, and our collaborators, Peter Curnow and Peter Sims,

544
00:32:26.774 --> 00:32:30.534
and our funders at NCI and Holobionation. Thank you. Happy to take questions.

545
00:32:36.774 --> 00:32:39.194
Please come to the microphone for any questions.

546
00:32:43.434 --> 00:32:45.194
So very interesting talk, Dr. Hirwen.

547
00:32:46.654 --> 00:32:50.294
In thinking about the cell states that seem to be specifically

548
00:32:50.334 --> 00:32:54.114
sensitive to some of the different compounds, do you think that

549
00:32:54.174 --> 00:32:57.694
those drugs are suppressing individual compartments

550
00:32:58.194 --> 00:33:01.453
or driving the cells to a different state?

551
00:33:02.314 --> 00:33:05.714
So yeah, I kind of gloss over that quickly, but the

552
00:33:06.414 --> 00:33:09.974
answer is that the pipeline allows us to

553
00:33:10.034 --> 00:33:13.434
predict both, right? And so you can, depending on the reference that you're

554
00:33:13.494 --> 00:33:15.374
using for the

555
00:33:16.674 --> 00:33:18.714
drug perturbation data, you can say

556
00:33:20.034 --> 00:33:23.314
can we use this drug to push, for example, a stem-like population to a more

557
00:33:23.354 --> 00:33:26.654
differentiated one if the reference is the more differentiated population?

558
00:33:27.114 --> 00:33:30.874
Or if you're using normal cells, healthy glial cells,

559
00:33:31.254 --> 00:33:33.394
can you push this towards a more normal phenotype?

560
00:33:33.594 --> 00:33:34.994
And so you can predict both, but the

561
00:33:36.134 --> 00:33:38.114
real readout is in the validation, right?

562
00:33:38.354 --> 00:33:38.994
Can we see that

563
00:33:40.334 --> 00:33:41.214
population depleted,

564
00:33:42.074 --> 00:33:45.834
and determining the difference between are we killing those cells or are we

565
00:33:45.874 --> 00:33:47.274
pushing them to a different cell type?

566
00:33:47.754 --> 00:33:51.614
And so the answer is that in the validation, we should see

567
00:33:51.674 --> 00:33:55.194
if that's actually taking place and which one it is.

568
00:34:02.954 --> 00:34:04.054
All right. Well, thank you very much.

569
00:34:04.134 --> 00:34:04.514
Thank you.

570
00:34:11.674 --> 00:34:14.995
All right, so for the next talk, we had a speaker change, and I'm going to invite

571
00:34:15.054 --> 00:34:18.754
Dr. Guo to come up and talk about age-dependent lung

572
00:34:18.834 --> 00:34:22.794
vulnerability, identifying serum hyaluronic acid as a

573
00:34:22.814 --> 00:34:26.154
predictive biomarker of ADC-induced interstitial lung injury.

574
00:34:28.534 --> 00:34:32.194
Thank you, the co-chairs, for selecting us. And my name is Peng Guo.

575
00:34:32.674 --> 00:34:35.554
I'm going to present this work on behalf of our team.

576
00:34:36.354 --> 00:34:38.924
This is my disclosure. And

577
00:34:39.915 --> 00:34:40.674
as we all know,

578
00:34:41.794 --> 00:34:45.534
antibody-drug conjugates is revolutionizing the solid

579
00:34:45.574 --> 00:34:47.854
tumor therapy. And

580
00:34:48.774 --> 00:34:52.574
for the hundreds of the ADCs right now in the preclinical and the

581
00:34:52.634 --> 00:34:56.574
clinical practice, there is one special HER2 targeted ADC called the

582
00:34:56.614 --> 00:35:00.534
trastuzumab deruxtecan. We call it T-DXd for short or

583
00:35:00.594 --> 00:35:04.224
Enhertu. This is a benchmark ADC leading this

584
00:35:04.854 --> 00:35:08.634
revolution due to its superior clinical

585
00:35:08.734 --> 00:35:12.493
efficacy and broad indications. However, T-DXd

586
00:35:12.614 --> 00:35:16.354
is not perfect. Its clinical usage is significantly

587
00:35:16.364 --> 00:35:20.074
limited by its severe side effects, which is the

588
00:35:20.134 --> 00:35:22.874
interstitial lung disease. We call it ILD for short.

589
00:35:23.234 --> 00:35:27.094
So on average, the T-DXd induced ILD rate is

590
00:35:27.154 --> 00:35:30.914
about 15% across all the tumor types, and the fatal

591
00:35:30.934 --> 00:35:34.634
event rate is about 2.2%, highlighting a significant

592
00:35:34.774 --> 00:35:38.334
unmet medical need to diagnose and treat

593
00:35:38.974 --> 00:35:40.374
ADC-induced ILD.

594
00:35:41.514 --> 00:35:42.534
And previously,

595
00:35:43.354 --> 00:35:46.834
our lab has identified the perivascular macrophages.

596
00:35:47.334 --> 00:35:51.274
They are the major cell type directly engulfing the circulating T-DXd

597
00:35:51.294 --> 00:35:53.554
in the lung and later

598
00:35:54.374 --> 00:35:58.244
facilitate the off-target bystander killing effect and

599
00:35:58.394 --> 00:36:01.914
cause the ADC-induced ILD. And based on this

600
00:36:02.014 --> 00:36:05.554
finding, so we proposed we could use

601
00:36:05.634 --> 00:36:09.254
intravenous immunoglobulin IVIG to treat these

602
00:36:09.314 --> 00:36:13.054
AMs as a potential therapeutic approach for treating

603
00:36:13.074 --> 00:36:13.434
the

604
00:36:14.614 --> 00:36:18.574
ADC-induced ILD in the clinic, and we validate this result in the preclinical

605
00:36:18.634 --> 00:36:22.274
models. So last month, we are very happy to see the

606
00:36:22.294 --> 00:36:24.874
clinicians from McMaster University in Canada.

607
00:36:25.334 --> 00:36:29.154
So they reported they use IVIG successfully treat

608
00:36:29.274 --> 00:36:33.154
a breast cancer patient with grade 4 T-DXd-induced ILD.

609
00:36:33.794 --> 00:36:37.594
And our next goal is to develop a noninvasive companion

610
00:36:37.634 --> 00:36:41.474
diagnostic biomarker for predicting the ADC-induced

611
00:36:41.594 --> 00:36:44.854
ILD. And we start our study from the clinical studies.

612
00:36:45.774 --> 00:36:49.714
So in one of our retrospective study, and we

613
00:36:49.754 --> 00:36:53.714
collaborate with the pediatric oncologistWe use TDXD

614
00:36:53.814 --> 00:36:57.654
to treat pediatric and young patients with a very rare cancer

615
00:36:57.754 --> 00:37:01.454
called desmoplastic small round cell tumor, DSRCT.

616
00:37:01.834 --> 00:37:05.394
And surprisingly, we found TDXD does not induce

617
00:37:05.474 --> 00:37:08.574
ILD in these childhood and young patients.

618
00:37:08.894 --> 00:37:12.474
The ILD rate is 0%, compared with 16% in adult

619
00:37:12.514 --> 00:37:15.854
patients. And the similar clinical observation has

620
00:37:15.914 --> 00:37:19.114
also been made by the American

621
00:37:19.434 --> 00:37:23.414
oncologist. So in this PIPEN 1924 trial, which

622
00:37:23.454 --> 00:37:26.414
is led by the John Hopkins Children's Hospital, they

623
00:37:27.594 --> 00:37:31.554
use TDXD to treat the young patients with osteosarcoma,

624
00:37:31.654 --> 00:37:34.094
and they also observed similar findings.

625
00:37:34.434 --> 00:37:35.834
So in the TDXD,

626
00:37:36.794 --> 00:37:40.154
in the younger patients, they do not induce ILD.

627
00:37:40.514 --> 00:37:43.714
And we think these two clinical observations are not a

628
00:37:43.794 --> 00:37:44.774
coincidence.

629
00:37:45.614 --> 00:37:49.254
We hypothesized that the ADC-induced ILD

630
00:37:49.434 --> 00:37:53.294
may be age dependent, and we use it as our cutting point for

631
00:37:53.334 --> 00:37:57.134
our biomechanical studies. So we first establish a

632
00:37:57.234 --> 00:38:00.894
young and adult mouse model to study the TDXD induced ILD.

633
00:38:01.354 --> 00:38:05.254
For the young group, we use two weeks old mice, and for the adult group we

634
00:38:05.314 --> 00:38:09.294
use eight weeks old mice, and we treat them with ADC

635
00:38:09.354 --> 00:38:09.614
for

636
00:38:10.514 --> 00:38:12.374
90 days. And after 90 days,

637
00:38:13.334 --> 00:38:17.154
so we evaluated ILD rate. For young group is 0%, compared with the

638
00:38:17.334 --> 00:38:20.594
40% of the adult group, and this result is

639
00:38:20.714 --> 00:38:24.454
validated by measuring the lung weights and also pathological

640
00:38:24.554 --> 00:38:26.674
stainings and also the cytokine release.

641
00:38:27.414 --> 00:38:31.214
This study just confirmed that the ADC induced ILD is

642
00:38:31.274 --> 00:38:33.334
age dependent in the preclinical model.

643
00:38:34.214 --> 00:38:35.254
And next, we want to

644
00:38:36.734 --> 00:38:38.994
find if this age-dependent

645
00:38:40.314 --> 00:38:43.654
ILD is related to the ADC accumulation in the lung.

646
00:38:43.814 --> 00:38:47.734
And in this bio-distribution study, we found if we increase the age of

647
00:38:47.774 --> 00:38:51.604
the animal from two weeks to 10 weeks, you will see more and more

648
00:38:51.854 --> 00:38:53.934
TDXD accumulated in these animals.

649
00:38:55.294 --> 00:38:58.894
And so we hypothesized that this may be related to the AM

650
00:38:58.934 --> 00:39:02.554
subtypes. And we next perform a single-cell

651
00:39:02.654 --> 00:39:03.394
RNA sequencing,

652
00:39:04.454 --> 00:39:08.334
to analyze the cell population difference between the young and adult

653
00:39:08.374 --> 00:39:12.274
mice. And we found in the young mice, they have significantly less

654
00:39:12.794 --> 00:39:15.994
AMs compared with the adult mice. And not just

655
00:39:16.014 --> 00:39:19.994
the AM cell populations, the young AMs, they are

656
00:39:20.074 --> 00:39:22.254
also immature compared with adult mice.

657
00:39:22.634 --> 00:39:26.174
For example, for the expression of CTSB, this is a key

658
00:39:26.254 --> 00:39:30.194
enzyme which the cell use to cleave the ADC

659
00:39:30.234 --> 00:39:33.514
linker and facilitate bystander killing effect.

660
00:39:33.994 --> 00:39:37.814
So the CTSB expression in the young group is significantly

661
00:39:37.894 --> 00:39:41.514
lower compared with adult group. And there's another example, which is

662
00:39:41.574 --> 00:39:45.264
SPP1. This is the macrophage secreted factor, which could

663
00:39:45.394 --> 00:39:49.034
enhance endothelial barrier permeability and promote the ILD

664
00:39:49.334 --> 00:39:53.214
progression. And we found in the adult group, after ADC

665
00:39:53.254 --> 00:39:56.414
treatment, SPP1 level is significantly upregulated.

666
00:39:56.754 --> 00:40:00.514
However, the immature macrophages in the young group failed to be

667
00:40:00.594 --> 00:40:04.294
polarized into SPP1 positive state under the ADC treatment.

668
00:40:05.234 --> 00:40:08.574
And beyond the macrophages, we also look at the other cell populations

669
00:40:08.954 --> 00:40:12.814
change during the ADC treatment. And we find out in the adult

670
00:40:12.894 --> 00:40:16.774
group, so endothelial cells, after the ADC treatment, their

671
00:40:16.814 --> 00:40:18.374
numbers is significantly decreased.

672
00:40:18.674 --> 00:40:22.394
However, in the young group, we didn't see endothelial cell

673
00:40:22.734 --> 00:40:26.634
change. So that means the young mice has significantly less

674
00:40:26.694 --> 00:40:29.114
lung vascular damage compared with the adult mice.

675
00:40:29.544 --> 00:40:31.814
And it's not just about the endothelial cell numbers.

676
00:40:32.234 --> 00:40:35.954
So the TDXD also will activate the endothelial

677
00:40:35.994 --> 00:40:39.274
cell from a quiescent state to a more active state.

678
00:40:39.634 --> 00:40:43.574
And for example, so after the TDXD damage in

679
00:40:43.634 --> 00:40:47.534
the adult group, the endothelial cell will upregulate a very important enzyme

680
00:40:47.914 --> 00:40:50.354
called HYAL2. This is a key

681
00:40:50.414 --> 00:40:54.114
hyaluronidase. So the endothelial cell use it to

682
00:40:54.134 --> 00:40:57.383
remodel the extracellular matrix, ECMs,

683
00:40:58.014 --> 00:41:01.594
which this enzyme, HYAL2, will

684
00:41:01.874 --> 00:41:05.764
cleave the polymerized lung hyaluronic acid, and

685
00:41:05.914 --> 00:41:09.834
chop into small pieces. So this HA fragment will be released

686
00:41:09.953 --> 00:41:13.594
into the bloodstream, and we can use it as a serum biomarker to

687
00:41:13.633 --> 00:41:16.544
detect the early lung injury

688
00:41:16.614 --> 00:41:17.934
events.

689
00:41:19.034 --> 00:41:22.774
And sorry. In our next study, we measured the serum

690
00:41:23.134 --> 00:41:27.034
HA levels in the preclinical model, and after 90 days, we found only

691
00:41:27.094 --> 00:41:31.014
in the adult group, we see a significant HA level increase

692
00:41:31.094 --> 00:41:34.974
after the ADC treatment. And if we use this HA

693
00:41:35.054 --> 00:41:39.034
as a single biomarker, we can achieve AUC of 80% with a very

694
00:41:39.074 --> 00:41:40.694
good sensitivity and specificity.

695
00:41:41.314 --> 00:41:45.054
We next want to test this serum biomarker in the clinical

696
00:41:45.114 --> 00:41:48.794
setting. And we are very lucky in China, there is a serum

697
00:41:48.854 --> 00:41:52.494
biomarker panel, has already been approved for detecting liver

698
00:41:52.534 --> 00:41:55.814
fibrosis. This panel include four biomarkers, including

699
00:41:55.994 --> 00:41:59.554
HA, also type IV collagen, procollagen 3

700
00:41:59.614 --> 00:42:03.214
N-terminal peptide, and the laminin. They are all ECM gradients.

701
00:42:03.654 --> 00:42:07.644
And, so because this method is clinically available, we

702
00:42:07.714 --> 00:42:10.374
just need to repurpose them for detecting the

703
00:42:10.414 --> 00:42:13.874
ADC-induced ILD. And also, this

704
00:42:14.054 --> 00:42:17.994
detection is very cheap. It costs only $20 in China

705
00:42:18.034 --> 00:42:19.554
to detect all these biomarkers.

706
00:42:20.634 --> 00:42:24.434
So we conduct a pilot clinical trial to study the serum

707
00:42:24.474 --> 00:42:28.454
biomarker panels. And currently, we have collected about 30

708
00:42:28.474 --> 00:42:32.354
patients' data. And so far, for the HA as a

709
00:42:32.414 --> 00:42:35.254
single biomarker, we achieve AUC of

710
00:42:36.294 --> 00:42:39.494
74%. And if we combine HA with other

711
00:42:39.514 --> 00:42:43.314
fibrosis-related biomarkers, we can improve the AUC to

712
00:42:43.534 --> 00:42:46.454
93% with 90% sensitivity and

713
00:42:46.954 --> 00:42:50.822
85% specificity.And in our next slide, I'm going to

714
00:42:51.142 --> 00:42:55.122
show you these serum biomarker panels can be used for companion diagnosis.

715
00:42:55.602 --> 00:42:58.942
So this is a patient, 61 years old, female with

716
00:42:59.682 --> 00:43:03.522
gallbladder cancer. And in the beginning, so when we recruited her,

717
00:43:04.042 --> 00:43:07.462
she's in the control group without any ILD.

718
00:43:07.782 --> 00:43:11.462
You can see her lung CT image is good, and the HA

719
00:43:11.542 --> 00:43:14.442
level is good. However, along the TDX treatment, we

720
00:43:15.542 --> 00:43:17.522
saw a gradual increase in the

721
00:43:18.662 --> 00:43:21.022
serum biomarker levels, especially the HA levels.

722
00:43:21.762 --> 00:43:25.242
After one month, we saw the HA above the normal range.

723
00:43:25.602 --> 00:43:28.221
