I think this suggests that the mechanisms of resistance to

1992
01:57:21.354 --> 01:57:25.254
KRAS inhibitors are complicated and probably more work needs to be

1993
01:57:25.274 --> 01:57:27.774
done to really understand how these are working.

1994
01:57:28.064 --> 01:57:31.294
And it will be very interesting to see how the ongoing clinical trials that are

1995
01:57:31.314 --> 01:57:33.694
incorporating TEAD inhibitors with KRAS inhibitors turn out.

1996
01:57:35.954 --> 01:57:37.974
Moving now to TP53.

1997
01:57:39.474 --> 01:57:43.454
So even more than KRAS, TP53 is the

1998
01:57:43.594 --> 01:57:47.494
most commonly mutated gene in cancer, with

1999
01:57:47.514 --> 01:57:51.394
an estimated 50% of all cancers having a TP53

2000
01:57:51.434 --> 01:57:52.034
mutation.

2001
01:57:53.014 --> 01:57:56.654
So with this very high prevalence, it would seem that TP53 would be the

2002
01:57:56.814 --> 01:58:00.734
perfect target. You can get all these different cancer

2003
01:58:00.774 --> 01:58:01.154
types.

2004
01:58:02.034 --> 01:58:05.994
But what we've seen over the past 30 years is that TP53

2005
01:58:06.004 --> 01:58:08.274
is actually very hard to target,

2006
01:58:09.154 --> 01:58:11.054
with numerous failed attempts.

2007
01:58:12.314 --> 01:58:15.874
There's been adenoviral P53 gene therapy, MDM2

2008
01:58:15.894 --> 01:58:19.644
inhibitors, non-selective mutant P53 inhibitors, P53 vaccines.

2009
01:58:20.094 --> 01:58:21.934
The list actually could go on and on.

2010
01:58:21.954 --> 01:58:25.214
There were several very high-profile phase three trials that failed.

2011
01:58:25.514 --> 01:58:29.114
So P53 has proven to be a very

2012
01:58:29.154 --> 01:58:30.254
difficult target,

2013
01:58:31.994 --> 01:58:34.054
and I think there's a lot of different reasons for this.

2014
01:58:34.094 --> 01:58:37.783
So I think these repeated failures reflect some fundamental challenges with

2015
01:58:37.794 --> 01:58:41.614
targeting P53. First is that TP53 is a nuclear

2016
01:58:41.694 --> 01:58:45.584
transcription factor. It doesn't have a traditional druggable binding pocket,

2017
01:58:45.644 --> 01:58:48.154
so it's a little bit harder to go after.

2018
01:58:48.214 --> 01:58:52.194
Additionally, mutations in TP53 occur across the entire genome

2019
01:58:52.234 --> 01:58:55.534
with over 2,000 distinct variants identified in cancer.

2020
01:58:56.094 --> 01:58:59.814
So making it much harder to design compounds that are mutant selective

2021
01:59:00.474 --> 01:59:02.434
because you have so many that you need to think about.

2022
01:59:04.034 --> 01:59:08.014
Additionally, TP53 mutations are loss-of-function mutations, and these are

2023
01:59:08.054 --> 01:59:12.014
often accompanied by biallelic inactivation, and so mechanisms that are

2024
01:59:12.034 --> 01:59:15.094
going to restore the activity of one allele are probably insufficient.

2025
01:59:16.194 --> 01:59:19.974
And finally, TP53 mutant cancers tend to harbor many co-occurring

2026
01:59:20.114 --> 01:59:23.814
alterations that provide alternative survival pathways, and so

2027
01:59:23.914 --> 01:59:27.774
many mechanisms around whatever inhibitor you may be trying to throw at

2028
01:59:27.834 --> 01:59:28.114
this.

2029
01:59:29.214 --> 01:59:33.074
However, despite these challenges, people continue to try to

2030
01:59:33.094 --> 01:59:36.994
target TP53. People still want to go after it, and

2031
01:59:37.034 --> 01:59:38.174
there is some glimmer of hope.

2032
01:59:39.614 --> 01:59:43.394
I will note there was, just two months ago in "New England Journal of Medicine," a

2033
01:59:44.274 --> 01:59:47.434
positive phase one study of this TP53

2034
01:59:47.514 --> 01:59:50.414
mutant-selective Y-220C inhibitor.

2035
01:59:50.574 --> 01:59:54.554
So there's been previous positive phase one studies that didn't end

2036
01:59:54.594 --> 01:59:58.284
up turning out, but this is the latest one, so fingers

2037
01:59:58.334 --> 01:59:59.854
crossed. Hopefully, this one will be different.

2038
02:00:01.934 --> 02:00:05.834
Here, we saw wonderful and exciting data from Dr.

2039
02:00:06.034 --> 02:00:09.594
Bacon, who have attempted to tackle this challenge of

2040
02:00:09.654 --> 02:00:13.134
targeting TP53 using a synthetic lethality approach.

2041
02:00:13.854 --> 02:00:17.514
The combination of the thymidine analog TAS-102 and PARP

2042
02:00:17.554 --> 02:00:21.294
inhibitors has previously been proposed as a synthetic lethal approach for

2043
02:00:21.334 --> 02:00:25.134
TP53, and this combination is currently in an ongoing clinical

2044
02:00:25.193 --> 02:00:25.654
trial.

2045
02:00:26.954 --> 02:00:30.394
Interestingly, when they were examining this combination in model systems, they

2046
02:00:30.474 --> 02:00:34.014
found that this two-drug approach leads to G2 arrest in the

2047
02:00:34.054 --> 02:00:38.014
TP53 mutant cells, which could potentially be a mechanism of resistance by

2048
02:00:38.054 --> 02:00:41.394
impairing cell death. And so they, further

2049
02:00:41.774 --> 02:00:45.454
investigating this, they identified that this was mediated through the ATR pathway,

2050
02:00:45.934 --> 02:00:49.763
and by applying a WEE1 inhibitor, were able to release the cells from G2,

2051
02:00:50.194 --> 02:00:53.994
leading to mitotic death. So based on this, I think they proposed a

2052
02:00:54.054 --> 02:00:57.534
very elegant solution with a triplet approach

2053
02:00:57.894 --> 02:01:01.794
using serial dosing of TAS-102 and PARP inhibitor and WEE1

2054
02:01:01.814 --> 02:01:04.654
inhibitor to try to manage the toxicity.

2055
02:01:05.054 --> 02:01:05.834
Very thoughtful,

2056
02:01:08.234 --> 02:01:12.194
rational combination. And I think this work really highlights the

2057
02:01:12.234 --> 02:01:16.174
complexity of using synthetic lethality to target TP53 with

2058
02:01:16.194 --> 02:01:18.194
the many possible escapement mechanisms.

2059
02:01:18.234 --> 02:01:22.194
And I want to congratulate this team for continuing to try to tackle

2060
02:01:22.234 --> 02:01:22.734
this very

2061
02:01:23.614 --> 02:01:24.444
difficult problem.

2062
02:01:26.534 --> 02:01:28.554
Moving now to the presentation by Dr.

2063
02:01:28.794 --> 02:01:29.254
Kerwin,

2064
02:01:30.394 --> 02:01:34.074
and focusing here, transitioning to model systems, but

2065
02:01:34.154 --> 02:01:37.134
also rational combinations. I think this

2066
02:01:38.934 --> 02:01:41.094
presentation hit two of the pillars.

2067
02:01:42.474 --> 02:01:46.354
Here we saw that they utilized a model system to identify rational

2068
02:01:46.434 --> 02:01:50.194
combinations of drugs to target IDH mutant glioma, which is a

2069
02:01:50.214 --> 02:01:53.134
devastating and uniformly fatal disease.

2070
02:01:53.574 --> 02:01:57.114
They used single-cell RNA-seq from 20 patient samples to

2071
02:01:57.134 --> 02:02:00.914
identify three master regulator classes of IDH

2072
02:02:00.934 --> 02:02:04.794
glioma, and then they matched these classes to patient-derived cell line

2073
02:02:04.854 --> 02:02:08.642
models.Which they were then able to use to perform a drug screen

2074
02:02:08.682 --> 02:02:12.422
using OncoTreat to identify cell state-specific drug

2075
02:02:12.542 --> 02:02:16.262
candidates, enabling rational combination

2076
02:02:16.322 --> 02:02:20.022
strategies. So I thought this was a really elegant model

2077
02:02:20.642 --> 02:02:24.322
for trying to come up with these rational combinations, and I look forward to

2078
02:02:24.382 --> 02:02:26.302
seeing the validation in the

2079
02:02:28.782 --> 02:02:29.762
slices from the brain.

2080
02:02:32.322 --> 02:02:36.262
Whenever we talk about personalizing targeted therapy, we run into these

2081
02:02:36.322 --> 02:02:39.482
contrasting thoughts about approaches.

2082
02:02:39.762 --> 02:02:43.302
One of which involves understanding the genomic mechanism of growth and resistance

2083
02:02:43.322 --> 02:02:46.762
and using that to identify targets, and the other is moving to a more

2084
02:02:46.842 --> 02:02:50.482
functional-based approach, and involves establishing patient-derived tumor

2085
02:02:50.562 --> 02:02:53.252
models and evaluating ex vivo drug responses.

2086
02:02:53.862 --> 02:02:56.142
And this functional-based approach was the one that was

2087
02:02:57.242 --> 02:02:58.952
taken by Dr. Chachad and colleagues.

2088
02:02:59.502 --> 02:03:03.302
Here, they did the biopsies from the Phase 1 Tropion-Pan

2089
02:03:03.462 --> 02:03:06.902
tumor basket trial and implanted these into mice,

2090
02:03:07.782 --> 02:03:11.742
and were able to test the efficacy of ado-trastuzumab deruxtecan, so a

2091
02:03:11.802 --> 02:03:15.742
Trop2 antibody-drug conjugate. Here, they found a very high degree

2092
02:03:15.782 --> 02:03:19.742
of concordance in response rates between the PDXs and the patients.

2093
02:03:20.382 --> 02:03:22.762
And furthermore, the concordant PDX models

2094
02:03:23.822 --> 02:03:27.542
enabled the evaluation of drug combinations, and in this case,

2095
02:03:27.622 --> 02:03:31.182
identified dato-DXd and gemcitabine as a

2096
02:03:31.222 --> 02:03:33.102
potentially synergistic combination.

2097
02:03:33.642 --> 02:03:37.202
So here we see another excellent example of using a model

2098
02:03:37.302 --> 02:03:40.872
system to predict patient-specific responses, as well as

2099
02:03:41.042 --> 02:03:43.922
further enabling the evaluation of rational drug combinations.

2100
02:03:44.022 --> 02:03:45.832
So again, hitting two of these pillars.

2101
02:03:46.642 --> 02:03:47.452
Very nicely done.

2102
02:03:49.282 --> 02:03:52.852
And then finally, for our last abstract and our last pillar,

2103
02:03:53.622 --> 02:03:55.562
which was presented by Dr. Guo,

2104
02:03:56.402 --> 02:04:00.352
looked at predictors of toxicity in treatment from antibody drug conjugates,

2105
02:04:00.702 --> 02:04:04.262
specifically pneumonitis related to treatment with trastuzumab

2106
02:04:04.272 --> 02:04:08.122
deruxtecan. So pneumonitis is a rare but serious

2107
02:04:08.202 --> 02:04:11.222
side effect of trastuzumab deruxtecan that has been recorded

2108
02:04:11.302 --> 02:04:15.051
across the studies for T-DXd in different cancer types.

2109
02:04:15.622 --> 02:04:19.292
And importantly, this includes some Grade 5 toxicity, which

2110
02:04:19.702 --> 02:04:22.401
for those of you not familiar with that, that is death.

2111
02:04:23.102 --> 02:04:27.042
And this is really important when we think about moving T-DXd earlier and

2112
02:04:27.082 --> 02:04:30.062
earlier, and particularly in breast, we're moving it earlier and earlier

2113
02:04:30.142 --> 02:04:33.222
into adjuvant, neoadjuvant space.

2114
02:04:33.622 --> 02:04:37.542
We do not want death to be a potential side effect when we're trying to cure a

2115
02:04:37.582 --> 02:04:38.081
patient.

2116
02:04:40.162 --> 02:04:44.002
So here they did some elegant studies using aged mouse models,

2117
02:04:44.422 --> 02:04:48.002
and they found that endothelial cells have high levels of induction of

2118
02:04:48.062 --> 02:04:51.922
HYAL2 and TMEM2 activation, which leads to hyaluronic

2119
02:04:52.062 --> 02:04:53.682
acid release into the circulation.

2120
02:04:54.462 --> 02:04:57.562
And they were able to correlate levels of hyaluronic acid in the

2121
02:04:57.602 --> 02:05:01.482
circulation with the development of interstitial lung disease in a patient

2122
02:05:01.522 --> 02:05:05.122
cohort, which indicates the promising potential of this as a

2123
02:05:05.162 --> 02:05:09.022
diagnostic biomarker. And I think this is very exciting work.

2124
02:05:09.062 --> 02:05:12.562
I think still additional validation is needed, but any

2125
02:05:12.602 --> 02:05:13.692
advancement towards

2126
02:05:15.102 --> 02:05:19.082
improving our ability to predict or have early detection

2127
02:05:19.122 --> 02:05:21.722
of this potentially devastating toxicity is really welcome.

2128
02:05:24.002 --> 02:05:27.902
And so with that, I will conclude and just bring this all together

2129
02:05:28.022 --> 02:05:31.702
to say that targeted therapeutics are really entering an exciting new era

2130
02:05:32.242 --> 02:05:36.232
using data-driven approaches, and that the new model of developing

2131
02:05:36.262 --> 02:05:39.442
these targeted therapeutics is relying on these four pillars.

2132
02:05:39.482 --> 02:05:43.182
It's becoming increasingly more complex, but will hopefully lead to better

2133
02:05:43.222 --> 02:05:43.782
outcomes.

2134
02:05:44.682 --> 02:05:47.582
I just want to thank everyone who's presented in this session today.

2135
02:05:48.042 --> 02:05:51.402
Amazing work that all of the researchers and clinicians are doing here.

2136
02:05:51.831 --> 02:05:55.702
And especially thank you to the caregivers, advocates, and funding agencies who

2137
02:05:55.782 --> 02:05:59.171
support this research. But most importantly, thank you to the

2138
02:05:59.282 --> 02:06:01.222
patients who have donated their samples.

2139
02:06:01.562 --> 02:06:05.522
I think it's really important, particularly for those of you who don't see patients

2140
02:06:05.562 --> 02:06:09.282
in clinic, to remember that these are the people that we're doing all of this

2141
02:06:09.302 --> 02:06:12.202
for, and it really makes a huge difference to them.

2142
02:06:12.282 --> 02:06:13.582
So thank you all very much.
